description.text:
This is the first part of a series of projects intended for first year calculus students. In this series, students will learn how to use different mathematical equations to assess the properties of solids and containers. My apologies if the "X" and "x" thing is confusing, but in some situations formatting makes using an asterisk impossible, so big X is a variable, and little x is multiply.
In this first project we will be finding the generic equation for a lidless box we will 3D print by using a standard geometric equation. For instructions and equations read further.

Notes: I optimized this thing to be printed in ABS with maximum settings. I would recommend a skirt with an offset of 0mm (otherwise known as a brim) with 2-5 loops for ABS. As can be seen from the photo, an increased infill may be helpful as well.

For this project I used a free program from Autodesk called TinkerCAD. I have long been a user of AutoCAD which is a desktop drafting program from the same company. I used TinkerCAD to make it easier for educators and learners to be able to more easily replicate what I did. TinkerCAD is awesome because it's not only free, but it's easy to use. It also runs in your browser and has built in instructional lessons.
www.tinkercad.com The first part of this project will start with a standard rectangle. I wanted dimensions that wold be easy to work with, take a minimal amount of plastic, and print easily. Therefore I used the box tool to create an object that was 100x60x2mm. Next I used the box function again along with the hide function in order to make my "cuts" into my object. For this example I used X=20mm. At this point it is easy to see the dimensions X = 20mm will give use. We have a base of 60x20mm, two flaps with dimensions of 60x20mm, and two flaps with dimensions of 20x20mm.

description.header: Project: Volume of a lidless box
description.text:
Concept For the purpose of this experiment, imagine that we have a material such as paper or cardboard with dimensions of 100x60mm. Our lidless box is made by cutting out squares from the corners as seen in the "How I Designed This" section. The corners are then folded up to create a lidless box. If you will notice the image on the left looks a lot like the object we created, which will allow students to visualize this part of the project and tie it in to the next parts as well. Objective Help students visualize the math that they will be using and make it easy to see the real world applications. Audience Even though the overall project is designed for Calculus students, this part of the project can be used for algebra students as well. Preparation
  • Teachers and/or students who are creating a lidless box using their own values of X will need to have access to a computer with internet access and be logged on to a free TinkerCAD account.
  • Tinkercad is easier to use with a mouse than with a tablet or trackpad, so computer mice are recommended.
  • No previous 3D design experience is required for the students, although familiarity with Tinkercad would be helpful.
  • The instructor should be comfortable answering modeling questions about Tinkercad and be able to advise students to avoid design features that might cause printing difficulties (overhangs, delicate features, etc).
  • It is helpful to have students form into working groups of two or three so that they can collaborate on the design process. Having students work in groups is also helpful if you have a limited number of computers and/or limited 3D printer access.
    • Step 1: Standard Formula To find our generic equation, we will be starting with the standard formula for volume: V = area x height Step 2: Establish X For the purpose of this experiment, X will be an unknown equal to the length of one of the sides of the squares that we "cut" out of the original 100x60mm object. Step 3: Use X To Find Generic Equation Taking the standard formulas V = area*height and area = widthxheight, then subtracting X from the width and height to represent the squares we cut out, we are given: V = (100 - 2X)(60 - 2X) * X Step 4: Substitute for X V = (100 - 2(20))(60 - 2(20)) x 20
    = (100 - 40)(60 - 40) x 20
    = (60)(20)(20) V = 24,000mm^3
    = 24ml Results We have now used our conceptualization along with algebra to come up with an equation that will give us the volume of a lidless box created by starting with a 10060mm rectangle with squares cut out of the corners with dimensions of XX. No matter how big or small our squares are, we will be able to easily find the volume of the lidless box by using our equation: V = (100 - 2X)(60 - 2X) * X

I decided to start from scratch. This Right end to the X axis was created from scratch. The idler pulley is designed to accommodate the smaller pulley bearings used by HicTop. The linear bearings sleeve is closed and is press fit.
BTW, I did get ideas for parts of this from several other designs. I have, however, never seen a printed lead screw nut.

For the plastic nut, run the screw through it several times till it works smooth then put some graphite inside for lubrication. I find that graphite works pretty well with plastic screws and nuts. I used a 4mm screw and nut for the tensioner and 3mm screws and nuts for the x-rod standoffs.

Objectives We hoped by creating this students around schools could have a small ruler of their own to use in math class without having to go to the store and buy one. Audiences This ruler was made with students in mind, but it could be helpful to people of all ages. Whether they want an accurate measurement or they want assistance in drawing a straight line, it is up to them. Preparation There really is no prior knowledge needed to use this ruler besides knowing how to read and use all other standard rulers. Steps 1.) We defined the problem at hand: What would be useful to a teacher or student that we could make on a 3D printer?
2.) We came up with different ideas that we thought could possibly work.
3.) We narrowed down our ideas and did research on what had already been done and what it would take to make one.
4.) We defined the criteria and constraints that would be present while making this.
5.) We looked at which ideas of ours could work.
6.) We decided our best idea was to make a ruler.
7.) We created a design proposal to give to our teacher.
8.) We created the ruler on Inventor and printed out a prototype.
9.) We looked at what had been printed out and decided what needed to be fixed.
10.) We changed what we thought was needed and resubmitted the idea.
11.) Our final draft was printed out on the 3D printer.
12.) We posted the ruler to the competition and gave it to our teacher.

[EDIT 8/26/2017: I recommend the remix of my plinth :
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2502030
so you can print it out without supports. Cleaning up the supports is a pain when printing out my original design.] I saw a cool plinth on a Frostgrave wargaming thread: http://www.lead-adventure.de/index.php?topic=87575.0 I thought it looked really cool and just had to have it. So I sketched up something that looks similar to it in Sketchup and finished off in Blender. It's currently scaled for my statues which are large and have a base of 1 1/2". Please scale down appropriately (or up) for your figurine. If you want this plinth to work for a 1 inch base (25mm), then try printing at about 67 percent. The sketchup file, blender file and the STL are all included. Enjoy! Feel free to re-mix. Unless you slice off the top disk and print in two pieces, print with supports. Link to some notes on how I designed the cylindrical part of this plinth in sketchup:
http://dmscraft.proboards.com/post/50900/thread Painting Tips:
For stone statue plinth: Base coat with 2 or 3 coats of a warm black or very dark brown. Let dry thoroughly -- I do this under a box fan supported by 4 soup cans (away from water). Take a warm medium to light gray and load up a flat tipped broad (preferbly round) brush and brush out most of the paint on a paper towel or paper. Stipple (light stabbing perpendicular motion) on the paper to see a dotted pattern -- if it is a solid circle keep stippling on the paper until dots. Once dots appear, then carefully stipple those dots onto the dark base coat -- this should give you a nice stone effect. Repeat if necessary, scattering it all around well and even. If it is overdone just let it dry and rebase with black/dark brown and redo it.

This snowflake was created in a free program called Tinkercad. Use this snowflake as a reminder of the beauty of nature. This project is a benchmark assessment of using Tinkercad in grades four-sixth.   It was designed with basic knowledge of fractions and geometry .  Before beginning your snowflake, make sure you use the Tinkercad free tutorials. Some students learn better by completing each tutorial independently, while others require step-by-step assistance in a mini-group. Read on to learn how to use fractions, geometry, and Tinkercad tools to connect learning across the curriculum, and create your very own snowflake.

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator Z18

Learning Targets and Prior Knowledge: Overarching Student Learning Target:
I can create one part of a snowflake and then duplicate that part to make the whole snowflake. Individual Learning Targets:
I can login independently.
I can rename my project.
I can change the width of an object.
I can change the length of an object.
I can change the height of an object.
I can scale an object evenly.
I can rotate an object.
I can raise an object off of the work plane.
I can group multiple objects.
I can copy an object.
I can paste an object.
I can use the align tool.
I can use the mirror tool.
I can share my project via Google Drive Prior Knowledge:
Students began this 3D printing unit in Art directly after completing a math unit on fractions in the general education classroom. Preparation:
Students should complete all tutorials in tinkercad before beginning the project.
Students are grouped into pairs for peer coaching, peer critiquing, and final check of work.
Students should be able to problem solve Tinkercad login and Internet issues. Because we are working on Chromebooks the internet can be finicky. We developed a list of strategies and troubleshooting to help students solve these t4ech problems independently.
A mouse is a must-have for most students. Some students prefer to use the trackpad on their Chromebook. Step 1: Understanding the Math Use your prior knowledge of fractions to help understand the geometry of snowflakes. Look at realistic snowflakes, and read the book Snowflake Bentley by Jacqueline Briggs Martin to deepen your understanding. Notice how snowflakes have six arms. Each arm appears to be be symmetrical with a mirror image of the arm on the opposite side of the snowflake. Divide the whole snowflake (360 degrees) into six parts. That would give each arm a sixt degree angle. Step 2: Getting Started with One Arm Use the various shape, letter, and hole tools in order to create one arm of the snowflake. The arm should show both negative and positive space with varying heights. You can use the mirror tool to help make your arm symmetrical. You will have to rotate this side of the arm and align it with the other side as you see below. Step 3: Duplicating Because we learned that there are six parts to the snowflake you must group your arm together and duplicate it. To get the arm in to the correct spot, rotate it to a sixty degree angle using the first arm as a starting point. Repeat this step until you have added all six parts. Step 4: Reviewing Work: In your predetermined partner groups check your work against all of the learning targets. If your work looks complete you must check the following: Location on the Build Plane:
Work is resting at 0.0 on the build plane.
There are no parts going under the build plane.
Nothing is floating above the build plane.
The build plane is clean. There are no objects that do not belong. Extending Parts:
There are no parts extending out from your object with space underneath. The printer cannot print in the air. All parts that are extending out must be at most at a 45 degree angle. Step 5: Sending Work If your project has met all of the learning targets and is printable send it to the teacher. Make sure you name your project with your first and last name, as well as your teacher's name. You will have three chances to have your work printed. If your project has errors, you will be notified and given the chance to fix it. Differentiation of Learning: Every teacher has students who need extra support and students who are ready for more challenge. Make sure you allow your students to have the choice of differentiating their own learning. For instance, students who are ready for more complex work can create something other than a snowflake as long as they meet all of the learning targets. One student was able to meet all of the learning targets while creating a minecraft structure. Student choice is important. Alex discusses how he met the Overarching Learning Target, as well as individual learning targets.

description.text: I Bought an acrylic case for my Pi a while ago it was a great design - but it broke. I don't know why I didn't think of this sooner, but I ended up designing it so the exact case could be 3D printed. I made some modifications which made it better than the original. This will work with the Raspberry Pi B+ and the Raspberry Pi 2. The lid is hinged, so you can get at the pins without taking it apart. I will be designing a bracket, to be able to stack these, since in my case, I have multiple, I would like to have them neatly stacked. Stay tuned for that. UPDATE: This box also fits a Raspberry Pi 3. I've heard heat is an issue for the Pi 3s, so I've updated taller walls, a back piece with vent holes, and a new top to screw in a 40mm fan. These have the "Tall" prefix added to the filename. Lastly, I've added another set of plastic "pads" near the front, similar to the ones at the rear, so the front is no longer sitting on pins.

Printer:

Rapide Lite 200

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

20%

Notes: Nothing fancy here. they're all flat objects, very simple to print. Tolerances are pretty tight for the slots, but I didn't need to do any filing. They snapped together perfectly. Depending how rigid you want the pieces to be, you can increase the infill, however mine's great at 20% Since I print on a Borosilicate sheet, I designed it so that all the flat, smooth surfaces are facing outward, simply for a neater finish.
Designed using Solidworks. if you have any suggestions, or comments, let me know I can add them to a revision.

description.text:
I recently swapped out the radio in my 2006 Hyundai Sonata, and in the process I discovered that there are a bunch of clips that hold the dash trim in place. 
These clips seem to have a tendency to get lost inside the vehicle, so I made a rough replacement part. I ended up using several when I was putting everything back together, they seem to work well enough although I believe they make for a slightly tighter fit than the original clips.
Hopefully these come in handy for someone else! From what I can gather these clips are used on Hyundai vehicles from other years and in other models too - so maybe someone else will be after one someday.
I'd recommend printing with a small nozzle - 0.4mm or below. I printed mine with a 0.8mm nozzle, and they didn't exactly come out pretty - but they did work, so close enough.

Doesn't Matter

description.text:
Super simple droid build, orange caps hold two part base together. The uploaded size creates a 6" ball, approximately 7.5" tall. Ball is hollow if anyone wishes to build electronics. Another one-off birthday present for my daughter who is in love with BB-8. Print six Body_Caps and Body_Rings, print two Body sections. Body_Rings hold the two Body parts together, Body_Caps fit inside Body_Rings to hide seams. I was pleased with most of the fit but it did require some shaping and sanding. I recommend printing one Body_Ring and Body_Cap after you print the Body sections and adjust as necessary. Credit for original design goes to Disney and Industrial Light and Magic (thank you for the inspiration!). 3D files were created in Cinema 4D based on visual interpretation of images posted on the web. BB-8 has a 2.0 dome! All dome files have been modified, download them all for a complete upgrade. Added an orange detail ring to the bottom of the dome to better match the real BB-8. Parts fit snuggly, if you have a heat gun you can soften the plastic just enough to mold it to a matching piece. Go slow and don't overheat the piece or you may be printing it again! I've added a 'Light' version of the body file. If you don't need the spherical interior this file will reduce the amount of plastic used for the print. UPDATE
BB-8 has 3.0 side panels! New side panel files have been created, download all 'caps' and 'inserts' to upgrade your BB-8! I've been working on these for a while, I recently found a good resource on how the panel lines work out. Print two sets of panel C, the pattern is used on plane F as well. I've left the original cap file online, it's been renamed to 'BB-8_Body_SimpleCap.stl'. Maker beware! I haven't had a chance to print these files and post updated images, I've been careful to provide the same amount of 'nesting' space for the inserts I did for the 2.0 dome. If you have trouble fitting the inserts into the panels please let me know! Let me know if you are interested in any other modifications!

Printer Brand:

MakerBot

Printer:

MakerBot Replicator Z18

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

10%

Notes: Used 3 shells because I knew I would have to sand and shape certain areas, YMMV.

This is a simple plane to build and cover and easy project for age 8+
VERY CURRENT, WORK IN PROGRESS!! MORE PICS COMING SOON, VIDEO OF MY SECOND BUILD AFTER THAT ON MY YOUTUBE CHANNEL, anyone who builds one before end of march may have it featured in my video if you send pics/videos!!! Updates: 2/26/16 updated right & left wing rib files to fix build tightness on top rear notches, thinned them by one layer and updated helping hands accordingly. 2/27/16 made gear more realistic size. WHAT YOU NEED
Need to outsource balsa wood 1/8" rods, glue, and covering then print:
17 total body ribs, 24 total wing ribs and tailfin builds a glider
add gear parts and Styrofoam floats for float glider, or
add nose cone, a few paper clips, rubber band and a prop for a band glider.
R/Cers there are included ailerons for micro setups! Notes: On my printer (which isn't working so great right now) this works out to 3 and 4-layer parts (mostly) so the whole thing took about 1/8 spool of filament and all of it prints in about 4 hours for the basic model. I used 80% infill for little more strength and had to turn the infill to 0 degrees from 45 for the control&gear2 file only. I'd love to see how pretty it could be from a properly working printer... Assembly:
Step 1: if using landing gear glue gear to front & back of fuse part 4, if using floats glue gear to front of fuse part 3 and rear of part 5.
Step 2: All the fuselage parts are numbered on back, or check DIAGRAM.stl and start by sliding them in order into the helping hands parts, press the balsa rods into the notches starting with side notches, assemble entire length with all rods in place and remove helping hands pieces BEFORE gluing rods to ribs (a rubber band every other rib section helps hold loose spots in until ready to glue)
Step 3: Use helping hands pieces to assemble wing sections similarly to fuselage, or see DIAGRAM.stl, BUILD BOTH 12 Piece halves separately and flat!
Step 4: glue wing halves together by placing one wing half on flat surface then sandwiching a balsa rod longer than the wings (this for mounting later) in between wing halves, and supporting one side until the tops touch and can be glued together, the ends of the raised side should be level and about 1 1/4" or 3cm off of the surface
Step 5:slide fins onto rear of fuselage and glue in place.
Step 6: hand sand any rough corners or edges smooth, then cover with any heat shrink material, and use hairdryer to shrink tight to frame. tape rudder fin behind last upright on fuse with one vertical piece of tape on each side, so it can be bent for maneuvering later.
Step 7: if using rubber band flier install propeller with shaped clip in nose part and install band and clip in back rib of fuselage. If not glue oval washer to front of fuselage.
Step 8: use rubber bands to secure wings in place and tape pieces to balance plane so that it balances side to side at the center of the fuselage, and front to back at about the middle of the wings.
Step 9: GIVE IT A TOSS! you're done except for fine tuning, which will be part of a soon to come video on my youtube channel ADDENDUM: if you are an R/Cer there are control surfaces as part of this print secure them where needed with tape similar to the rudder, add your Rx, micro servos and motor and send me some video!! There should be enough play in the tailfin that's whole if there isn't cut it on its groove and use tape as with the other control surfaces

Cookie guidelines This is laid out for 2.5"x5" cookie bars. Put a thick layer of the proper color frosting on the baked cookie bars, then throw them in the fridge for a few hours to firm up the frosting before using this device to cut the brick pattern into the topping. I used chocolate chip cookie base with vanilla frosting with food coloring; there is commercial yellow frosting available, but what I find is lemon, which wouldn't have gone well with my chocolate chip cookie, but would go well with other cookie types. And, of course, you can also use it to make non-yellow bricks, for whatever need you have!
